## Project Description

This project investigates the relationship between snowmelt dynamics and downstream streamflow response in the Boulder Creek watershed of the Colorado Front Range. Using paired records of Snow Water Equivalent (SWE) from SNOTEL stations and daily discharge from USGS stream gauges, the analysis quantifies the timing and magnitude of snowmelt-driven runoff.

**Central Research Question:**
> [Your specific research question — e.g., "How does the timing of peak SWE at Front Range SNOTEL stations predict peak discharge at Boulder Creek, and has this lag relationship shifted over the past two decades?"]

**Why this matters:** Snowmelt is the dominant source of water supply across the Colorado Front Range. Understanding the lag between snowpack conditions and streamflow is critical for [water allocation planning / drought forecasting / reservoir operations — fill in what applies to your partner's context].

